            </sec>
            <sec>
                <title>3.2 Temporal coverage</title>
                <p id="S3.2">The inventory of surveys covers data that has been collected from the 1960s until 2020. Most collect data in a single round only, which could take anywhere from a few weeks to several years to complete. Other surveys collect data on the same population in multiple rounds &#x2013; an aspect of survey design that we will discuss in 
                    <xref ref-type="other" rid="S3.4">Section 3.4</xref>. Data collection for such surveys can cover much longer periods, up to several decades. In the inventory of surveys, we have included the first and last year of data collection, to the best of our knowledge.
                    <sup>
                        <xref ref-type="other" rid="FN4">4</xref>
                    </sup>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <xref ref-type="fig" rid="f3">Figure 3</xref> displays the data collection period for each survey. The period is the interval between the first and last year of data collection, regardless of the frequency of data collection in between. In multi-round surveys, data might be collected annually during this time span, or less often, or at less regular intervals.</p>
