            <sec>
                <title>3.5 Survey items on migration aspirations</title>
                <p id="S3.5">Survey items that enquire about migration aspirations can be broken down in terms of their 
                    <italic toggle="yes">mindset</italic> and a
                    <italic toggle="yes">ction</italic>. Here, we discuss the 
                    <italic toggle="yes">nature of the mindset</italic> of the items. For more information about the composition of survey items on migration aspirations, see 
                    <xref ref-type="bibr" rid="ref-48">Carling (2019)</xref> and 
                    <xref ref-type="bibr" rid="ref-49">Carling &amp; Mjelva (2021)</xref>.</p>
                <p>The nature of the mindset can broadly be described as a person&#x2019;s thoughts and feelings about the prospect of migration. 
                    <xref ref-type="bibr" rid="ref-48">Carling (2019)</xref> identified eight types of mindsets: consideration, preference, willingness, necessity, planning, intention, expectation, and likelihood. A description of these mindsets is found in 
